         Yahoo’s product costs are soaring; revenue isn’t
    








    By
        
        John Shinal

Published: Oct 16, 2013 12:25 p.m. ET

Share


















































 



 


        Commentary: Mayer’s investments have yet to pay off
    












By

                                        JohnShinal











Bloomberg



Marissa Mayer logged more than a dozen years at Google before taking the helm at Yahoo in July 2012.

Yahoo Inc. CEO Marissa Mayer has been hiring product engineers this year with the same gusto as when she was a top executive at Google Inc. The problem with that strategy is that Yahoo 

                            
                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                  
                                    US:YHOO

                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                         unlike its larger rival 

                            
                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                  
                                    GOOG, +0.49%

                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                         isn’t seeing any revenue boost yet from its investments. Product-development costs surged 23% in the third quarter, compared with the same period a year ago, while revenue slipped 3% on a year-over-year basis (minus traffic-acquisition costs, or TAC). That helps explain why Yahoo’s third-quarter operating income showed a year-over-year drop of 39%, after that important metric had climbed 44% during the first six months of 2013. Yahoo reported its third-quarter results late Tuesday.  Much of that higher spending was due to the acquisition of Tumblr, which Yahoo bought earlier this year for close to $1 billion, and whose operating expenses are now counted on Yahoo’s income statement, according to CFO Ken Goldman But Mayer has also been on a hiring binge at Yahoo, especially in engineering, bringing 1,000 engineers aboard so far this year. Sales and marketing costs also rose, climbing 5% on a year-over-year basis.







While Yahoo’s total operating costs in the quarter were held flat from a year ago, at $1.05 billion, they would have risen if the company hadn’t booked a restructuring charge in the year-earlier period. Mayer and CFO Goldman both said during the company’s earnings conference call Tuesday that expenses are expected to level off in 2014. That may be just in time for Yahoo shareholders, since the company also issued a fourth-quarter revenue forecast range that was slightly below Wall Street’s earlier expectations. The new forecast signals that Yahoo will post either little or no top-line growth in 2013, Mayer’s first full year at the helm, even though the company’s number of paid search clicks rose 21% in the third quarter. The just-completed quarter saw a huge decline in another important Yahoo metric: cash flow from operations. Net operating cash plunged 72% during the quarter, compared with a year earlier, and is down 48% for the first nine months of this year. All this might be cause for alarm if not for Yahoo’s lucrative stake in Alibaba, the biggest online-commerce company in China.



Earnings Wall
Discuss key earnings announcements before and after results come in. Learn more



Some Wall Street analysts estimate that at least half of Yahoo’s $34 billion market valuation is owed to its Alibaba shares, which are expected to soar in value with an Alibaba IPO. Sources have told this column that the offering will come next year, and Goldman said Tuesday that Yahoo does “expect that Alibaba will IPO at some point,” though he didn’t offer any time frame.  Yahoo said it had amended a prior agreement with Alibaba and will now sell at least 208 million shares of the company in any IPO, down from at least 261.5 million shares previously.  Yahoo invested $1 billion in Alibaba in 2005, in exchange for a 40% stake, and still owns about a quarter of the company. Once it does sell Alibaba shares, Yahoo will be able to book extraordinary gains from those transactions for at least several quarters, as it did after selling a large Alibaba stake last September. Yahoo has been using the gains from that sale to fund investments and buy back shares, thereby reducing its share count and raising per-share earnings. Even as it does, Yahoo will continue to benefit from its equity interests in both Alibaba and Yahoo Japan, as it did in the third quarter. Yet the gains from any Alibaba share sales will be booked in a limited number of quarters, even as Yahoo’s operations continue to struggle. And investors just got a preview of what Yahoo’s financials might look like after the Alibaba gains are gone. On a GAAP basis, Yahoo’s net income plunged by 91% in the third quarter to $297 million, or 28 cents per share. That’s because last year’s third-quarter earnings line ballooned by $2.8 billion with the sale of Alibaba shares.  And 78% of net income for the third quarter was due to what’s called “earnings from equity interests” on Yahoo’s income statement — which is primarily from the investments in Yahoo Japan and Alibaba. That line rose to $233 million. In other words, less than a quarter of Yahoo’s net profit came from its own operations. Investors whose optimism has helped drive a doubling of Yahoo’s share price since Mayer took the CEO job in July 2012 should be aware that they’re making a bet on a revenue turnaround that has yet to materialize. Unless Yahoo’s investments begin to boost its top line, growth investors should be nowhere near this stock once the company has booked most of the financial gains from its Alibaba share sales.  Note: The author has no positions, long or short, in Yahoo or any of its rivals. 


