 Join NowGO»Yahoo Inc. - Breaking Up Is Hard To Do But Profitable - 11% UpsideFeb. 2.15 | About: Yahoo! Inc. (AABA) Roundabout Asset Management Special situations, quantitative, hedge fund managerRoundabout Asset Management LLCSummarySpin-off of Alibaba shares is a significant valuation catalyst.Upside of 11.2% should be realized in less than twelve months.Recent concerns over tax-minimizing corporate transactions has presented this opportunity.Background
On January 27, 2015 Yahoo! Inc. (YHOO) released its 4Q14 earnings. As part of the release, YHOO informed shareholders that it would spin-off the remainder of its stake in Alibaba Group (NYSE:BABA) in a tax-free manner to shareholders. Based on a sum-of-the-parts analysis, YHOO shares are trading at a significant discount to fair value and provide an attractive opportunity for investors.
Company Description
Founded in 1994 by Jerry Yang and David Filo, YHOO is a global Internet media company that offers communications, content, and a community platform that delivers consumer experiences and advertising solutions across digital screens. Revenues are derived between Search (40.5%), Display (37.8%) and Other (21%).
The Company has struggled in recent years with competition from Google, Facebook, and other social media platforms, as indicated by revenue contraction in seven out of the past eight quarters.
CEO Marissa Mayer was hired in 2012 to turnaround the failing core business, but improvements have yet to materialize. The significant rise in YHOO shares since her hiring are due to the Company's holdings of Alibaba Group and Yahoo! Japan Corp. (OTCPK:YAHOY).
Spin-Off Details
The spin-off of BABA shares to YHOO shareholders is expected to occur in the 4Q15 after YHOO's lock-up expires in September 2015. The "SpinCo" will house all of YHOO's remaining shares in BABA and a legacy, ancillary, operating business of Yahoo ("Active Trade or Business", or "ATB"). The SpinCo will assume no debt and YHOO will retain its cash.
The transaction still requires Board, IRS, and SEC approval. Most importantly, the Company will look to the IRS to provide a favorable ruling in regard to the tax-free nature of the deal. The proposed transaction is similar in nature to the recent spin-off of Liberty TripAdvisor Holdings Inc. (NASDAQ:LTRPA) from Liberty Ventures (NASDAQ:LVNTA) in 2014, which we use as a proxy for timing purposes.

The pro-forma structure of YHOO and SpinCo is as follows: 
Opportunity - 11% upside in ~11 months
The spin-off of LTRPA from LVNTA took 321 days between announcement to completion, and I believe this transaction should be no different.
The valuation framework deployed below contains a few assumptions that err on the side of conservatism.

Given that the SpinCo will not be a "pure-play" the shares will trade at a discount to BABA shares. However, given that the ATB will likely be immaterial compared with the value of the BABA shares (~$35 billion) and relatively equal liquidity between the SpinCo shares and BABA shares (SpinCo will have 383.6 million BABA shares vs. the 320.106 million shares offered in the IPO). I estimate that the discount will be minimal and likely in the neighborhood of 0%-2%.
Assuming this transaction goes forward, shareholders can expect YAHOY to be spun-off in a similar manner, however, given the potential taxable event, I have assigned a 10% discount.
For the core YHOO business I am using the average analyst estimated EBITDA for FY15 and applying a 4.0x EV/EBITDA multiple. This multiple is significantly below comps and below analysts' estimates who favor using a higher multiple (closer to 5.0x by my estimates) on a higher 2016 EBITDA level. According to one analyst, the peer group trades at 6.7x EBITDA (implying that I am using a 40% discount to peers).
I apply a 7.5% discount to YHOO's net cash position as while I believe Yahoo's management will remain good stewards of capital (the Company has reduced gross shares outstanding by 29% since 2012 for $9.4 billion), there could be potential for dilutive spending by management. The Company has said that it anticipates returning ~50% of the after-tax proceeds to shareholders so we know that at least half of the cash on hand will not be used inappropriately.

In addition to the individual component discounts, I apply a 15% "HoldCo" discount to the remaining YAHOY, YHOO Core Business and YHOO Net Cash as I believe the Street will ultimately assess a sum-of-the-parts discount on the HoldCo.
Risks
Core YHOO continues decline: Revenue ex-TAC and adjusted EBITDA were down 1% and 13% respectively in 2014 and analysts are estimating that revenue and EBITDA will fall 5.1% and 17% respectively in 2015 according to Bloomberg. While Mayer has tried to stabilize and grow the business, there is no guarantee that she will be successful in the near future. The valuation framework used considers this fact and if the core business turns around there is additional upside for shareholders.
Unfavorable IRS ruling: While YHOO has enlisted the help of tax advisors before announcing the spin-off, and even considering the LTRPA spin-off, there is no guarantee that the IRS will allow the tax-free deal. If the IRS does not give its approval, shareholders are likely to value YHOO assuming BABA and YAHOY are fully-taxed, which could push shares of YHOO down to $31.50 (28% downside).
Technical Details
In order to capture the spread described in the valuation section investors should short 0.40 shares of BABA for every one share of YHOO and short 2.10 shares of YAHOY for every one share of YHOO (this refers to the shares traded in Japan and not the ADR that this article references). These ratios will ensure YHOO shareholders are not impacted by the changes in BABA and YAHOY share prices. Borrowing costs are currently minimal.
Conclusion
While the arbitrage community may be somewhat apprehensive about tax-related deals after the recent fallout from the Shire/AbbVie cancelled merger, the spin-off of BABA shares from YHOO is far less likely to run into any trouble with the IRS and the current upside makes this an attractive situation.
Disclosure: The author is long YHOO. 
The author wrote this article themselves, and it expresses their own opinions. The author is not receiving compensation for it. The author has no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article.

Additional disclosure: I am long YHOO and short BABA and 4689.JP in order to lock in the spread. I may change or exit my position (buy or sell shares) without updating this article and without informing the Seeking Alpha community.
